      "actual_answer_summary": "The snapshot provides a layered but incomplete evidence map. Product testing found DBP and DEHP in all 11 tested sanitary-pad brands, while package air was sampled for volatile compounds. Workplace sampling found six phthalates in every tested nail salon, with DEHP highest on silicone wristbands. Human biomonitoring detected DEP, DBP, and DEHP in all 20 menstrual-blood samples and BPA in 13. Receptor bioassays showed estrogen agonism in three tested hair-product samples. Epidemiologically, daily hair-oil use near 36 weeks was associated with 8.3 fewer gestational days after adjustment for race. A mechanistic review found anti-androgenic activity for BP-1, BP-2, and BP-3 in cited assays. Together, these findings support product presence, environmental and biological exposure, biological activity, and an association with a health outcome, but they do not establish that one specific product caused that outcome. The evidence remains limited by small or selected samples, self-reported or incompletely characterized product use, unknown formulations and doses, possible exposure from non-product sources, and assay or sampling limitations. Minimum additional evidence would be a chemically verified, product-specific exposure assessment linking the product to internal dose; a replicated prospective epidemiologic design with temporally appropriate repeated biomarkers, a defined health outcome, adequate size, and control of major confounding; and convergent experimental evidence showing that exposure levels plausibly reached by users produce the relevant receptor or mechanistic effect and outcome. Ideally, product removal or replacement would reduce exposure and risk. Without that chain from verified product composition to dose, mechanism, temporality, and replicated outcome, a product-specific causal health claim is unsupported.",
